1.  TYPE OF DATA

1.1  Parameter/Measurement.  These datasets consist of the deviation of
seasonal total ozone for various regions and deviations of seasonal layer
ozone for various regions from ozonesonde and Umkehr.

1.2  Unit of Measurement.  Ozone deviations are measured as a percentage of
established ozone values for each particular time, location, and pressure
level.

1.3  Data Source.  These datasets described are composed of mean-monthly
ozone values published in "Ozone Data of the World", published bimonthly in
Downsview, Canada, by the Atmospheric Environment Service, Department of
the Environment, in cooperation with the the World Meteorological
Organization (WMO).  The total ozone measurements were obtained from
ground-based Dobson spectrophotometers and Soviet Union M-83 broadband-
filter instruments (ozonometers).  The layer ozone measurements were
obtained from in-situ ozonesonde measurements and indirect Umkehr
measurements.  The Umkehr measurements are based on the change in the
relative intensity of radiation (in adjacent wavelengths) scattered from
the zenith sky as the sun rises and sets.

1.4  Data Set Identification.  These datasets consist of level III data and
are referred to as Angell's Percent Deviation of Seasonal Total Ozone,
Angell's Percent Deviation of Seasonal Layer Ozone from Ozonesonde, and
Angell's Percent Deviation of Seasonal Layer Ozone from Umkehr.

2.  SPATIAL CHARACTERISTICS

2.1  Spatial Coverage.  As a result of the varying availability and density
of ozone measuring stations worldwide, global coverage for seasonal
deviations was not obtained,therefore, near global coverage have been
obtained through the use of regional averages.  To enable filtering within
the NASA Climate Data System, the regions that compose these data are
represented by numerical values.  The regions associated with the total
ozone deviations, Europe(1), North America(2), Asia(3), USSR(4), north
polar(5), north temperate(6), tropics(7), south temperate(8), south
polar(9), and world(10) are represented by the numerical values 1 through
10 respectively.  The regions associated with the layer ozone deviations
from ozonesonde, north polar(1), south polar(2), south temperate(3), and
north temperate(4) are represented by the numerical values 1 through 4, and
the regions that compose the layer ozone deviations from Umkehr, south
temperate(1), north polar(2), tropical(3), and north temperate(4) are also
represented by the numerical values 1 through 4.

2.2  Spatial Resolution.  This data set is composed of regional averages
covering nearly the entire globe.  The layer ozone data from ozonesonde
consist of layer averages for the north polar, south polar, south
temperate, and north temperate regions.  The layer ozone data from Umkehr
consist of layer averages for the south temperate, north polar, tropical,
and north temperate region.  The total ozone data consist of total column
measurements for Europe, North America, Asia, USSR north polar, north
temperate, tropics, south temperate, south polar, and world.  The seasonal
deviations from ozonesonde consist of measurements for the 2-8 km, 8-16 km,
16-24 km, and 24-32 km level, with each layer represented by the single
value 5 km, 12 km, 20 km, and 28 km respectively.  The seasonal deviations
from Umkehr consist of measurements for the 2-8 km, 8-16 km, 16-24 km, and
24-32 km level, with each layer represented by the single value 5 km, 12
km, 20 km, and 28 km respectively.  The total ozone deviations consist of
total vertical column measurements.

3.  TEMPORAL CHARACTERISTICS

3.1  Temporal Coverage.  The layer ozone deviations data cover the period
December 1967 through November 1989.  The total column ozone deviations
cover the period December 1957 through November 1990.

3.2  Temporal Resolution.  These data sets consists of seasonal values of
ozone deviations.  Each season consist of a three month period, as follows:
winter (December, January, February), spring (March, April, May), summer
(June, July, August), and fall (September, October, November).

4.  INSTRUMENT DESCRIPTION

4.1  Mission Objectives.  The objective of these data sets are to assist
researchers in the study of manmade and natural events that influence and
are influenced by the fluctuations in ozone levels over time.  Some of the
areas of study include the relationship between ozone and sunspot activity
(Angell, 1989), anthropogenic influences on the atmosphere, and the
relationship between ozone levels and the Quasi-Biennial Oscillation
(Labitzke and van Loon, 1988, 1988, 1989, and Angell, 1986) and Southern
Oscillation Index, etc.

4.2  Key Satellite Flight Parameters.  None

4.3  Principles of Operation.  None

4.4  Instrument Measurement Geometry.  None


5.  DATA PROCESSING SEQUENCE

5.1  Processing Steps and Data Sets.  The monthly ozone measurements
obtained from "Ozone Data for the World" are used directly in the
calculation of both total and layer ozone deviations.

5.2  Derivation Techniques/Algorithms.  The total ozone deviations are
calculated as the average of reporting stations within each region with the
exception of north temperate, hemispheric, and world values which are
computed from various weighted averages of smaller regions.  North
temperate values are derived from an equal weighting of values calculated
for the Soviet Union, Europe, North America, and Asia.  The hemispheric
averages are computed from a 1-3-2 weighting of polar, temperate, and
tropical values.  The world averages are computed from a 1-3-4-3-1
weighting of north polar, north temperate, tropical, south temperate, and
south polar values.  The seasonal values are further computed from the
three months that compose each season, and are smoothed by means of a
5-point binomial smoothing, to reduce the complexity of the variations.
This smoothing technique uses a 1-4-6-4-1 weighting of seasonal values
divided by 16.  For computation of ozone deviations, reported ozone values
are compared to the mean values calculated for the period 1958-77, with the
exception of 1961-77 for the tropics, and 1973-77 for the Soviet Union.
Layer ozone deviations are also computed directly from "Ozone Data for the
World" in a similar manner as the total column ozone deviations.  The
Umkehr measurements for Europe, Japan, India, and North America are given
equal weighting in the computation of the north temperate averages, and the
ozonesonde measurements for the north temperate region are computed from a
2-2-1 weighting of values in North America, Europe, and Japan.  Mean values
for layer ozone deviations are based on data available through 1977.

5.3  Special Corrections/Adjustments.  None

5.4  Processing Changes.  Several processing changes have taken place since
these data were first released.  Total ozone deviations for Japan and India
have been combined with two new Dobson stations in China and are referred
to as the Asia region.  The Soviet M-83 data is only used after 1973, after
considerable improvements were made in instruments and observational
techniques. Finally the north temperate total deviations are now based on
an equal weighting of values for the Soviet Union, North America, and Asia.
Layer ozone deviations for the north temperate region are now based on an
equal weighting of values from Europe, Japan, India, and North America as a
result of 3 new reporting stations in North America.

6.  QUALITY ASSESSMENT

6.1  Data Validation by Producer.  The seasonal total column ozone values
have been compared with values obtained from the TIROS Operational Vertical
Sounder (TOVS) aboard the NOAA series of satellites and the Solar
Backscatter Ultraviolet (SBUV) instrument on Nimbus-7 by the data producer
(Planet, Miller, and Angell, 1988).  The comparison found that there was
good quantitative agreement till about mid 1984, with difference after that
time.  The greatest differences were found between the measurements
obtained by the SBUV and TOVS instruments. The best agreement between the
ground data and satellite data occurred in the north temperate zone with
the TOVS instrument, possibly due to a higher density of ground stations.
Agreement between ground data and satellite data in the south temperate
zone was not as good, possibly due to the poor sampling of ground data.  In
all zones there was qualitative agreement in trends of ozone values.

6.2  Confidence Level/Accuracy Judgment.  The accuracy of Umkehr- derived
ozone measurements is best at high stratospheric heights but is of little
reliability at tropospheric and low stratospheric levels.  It is also
important to note that values for ozone from high stratospheric levels can
be affected adversely by the presence of volcanic aerosols (Deluisi, 1979).
Ozone measurements from ozonesonde are not obtained at the high
stratospheric levels, but at lower levels the data obtained are considered
reliable.  The number and distribution of Dobson total-ozone stations is
considered to be unsatisfactory in the north polar, south temperate, and
south temperate regions due to the scarcity of stations.  It is also known
that the instruments have experienced calibration problems which have not
been taken into account when computing deviations.

6.3  Usage Guidance.  Users of these data should be aware of the
limitations.  Quantitative use of these data can be affected by a
calibration errors, scarcity of stations, presence of aerosols, and other
influences.  Qualitative use of this data in demonstrating trends is
considered more reliable.


